{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7439cbd6-7006-4aa9-83fd-6a4289aef060","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the recommended cross-platform .NET diagnostic tool and requires no install beyond a single dotnet tool command.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (default ~30s, Ctrl+C to stop)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### If you need OS-level detail (driver/kernel time):\n\nUse **PerfView** instead — it captures ETW events including kernel stacks:\n\n```powershell\n# Download PerfView.exe from https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases\nPerfView.exe collect -Duration:30 -CircularMB:500\n```\n\n### Which to pick?\n\n| Tool | Best for |\n|---|---|\n| `dotnet-trace` | Managed-code hot paths, quick & lightweight |\n| PerfView | Full-stack (managed + native + kernel), GC analysis |\n\nFor a CPU-pegged .NET service, start with `dotnet-trace` — it's the fastest path to a flame graph of where your CPU time is going.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"20949d3c-475d-4101-a45e-32ab3fef5d51","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question — no code changes or repo work needed. I'll give a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":398,"requestId":"A0CE:3C6161:C34092:F0C565:6A0130BE"},"id":"af08aca9-cb24-4f5e-8b3f-68a1dfdf68b9","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:28:43.505Z","parentId":"e79e68df-4bbe-4ce5-86e7-00408f5278c2"}
